    {
      "note_no": "15",
      "note": "I.e., equal in dignity with all other inmates of paradise. As regards the term atrab (sing, tirb), rendered above - as well as in 38:52 and 78:33 - as \"well-matched\", there is no doubt that it primarily denotes \"[persons] of equal age\" (a meaning adopted by most of the commentators); however, as pointed out by all philological authorities, this term is also used in the sense of \"[persons] equal in quality\", that is, \"well-matched\": a significance which, to my mind, is eminently appropriate here inasmuch as it is meant to stress the equal excellence of all who have attained to righteousness, whether they be men or women; or, alternatively, the equal attraction towards one another and, thus, a mutual fulfilment of their spiritual and emotional needs; or both of the above meanings."
